,Recommended,243200,25708200,"Posted: 26 September, 2016",all,Ves,"Developed by: Daedalic EntertainmentPublished by: Deep Silver / Daedalic EntertainmentGenre: Adventure, Point & ClickMemoria tells you a story of princess Sadja; the one who traveled from faraway land called Fasar to Drakonia- to fight demons in Gorian desert. Her own journey to reach the fortress was not easy, determined by her ambitions- she struggled to reach her own goals, but something happened, she disappeared, and her tale was forgotten.Control & GameplayIn this game, you will play through two different time periods as two main characters; Geron the bird catcher and Sadja the princess. Both characters have each unique stories and plots, Sadja as we know, she- pursuing her goal to be a hero, meanwhile in the present, Geron, wants to lift a curse from Nuri, her girlfriend. I expected I would not be confused with control, and I was right! It's so responsive and easy to recognize (as there are some tutorials at beginning), especially when you are familiar with Daedalic games, they have similarity of controls. The best part, Memoria has a feature to show POIs (Point of interests) which helps you to see some unnoticable items or POI, so you will be able to solve the puzzle in no time (well, some puzzles need more efforts, but they're not too difficult). There are also objectives and notes which can be handy especially when you accidentally skip a scene or dialogue. For both characters, inventories and magics are different, for example Geron has an ability to repair/destroy with magic, and he has Nuri's Necklace, while Sadja's ability to petrify, which make players have to remember a bit, but it's not that hard for there are just several items and magic.GraphicsFor the most part, truly magnificent. The attention to detail is lovable, the tomb of Malakkar for example, has nice detail of art, unique drawing, and beautiful lighting. They are seemed to be magically drawn and -- I can say it's beautiful, every detail really caught my attention. Every part of location has unusual look, and Yap! Memoria visually connects me to the game, which makes the game itself more enjoyable.AudioThe other part that I love from this game is the audio, like it's promised, Memoria has a subtle soundtrack and high-quality voiceovers. It was honestly fantastic, atmospheric; you can feel the relaxed, gripping, and quaint ambience. What I love the most is the voiceovers, their voices and accents actually fit to the characters and the game, and the dialogues aren't boring (as if it is a movie). Although the audio is almost perfect, I still encounter bugs where voices are missing.ConclusionMemoria is one of the best point-n-click adventure games I've ever played, sadly I avoid telling many good things here-- in case of spoilers. Even though there's still a little bug lives in the game, it doesn't really annoy you, but what I can say, the game is highly recommended for those who love puzzles, solving riddles, and artworks. It's so inspiring, really worth buying because of its features, and it's so enjoyable (YES, it's incredibly fun).Overall score: 4.8/5http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=769788179Nominated for an award."
