,Recommended,243200,16639370,"Posted: 22 June, 2015",all,talgaby,"Short version: 88%If the puzzles wouldn’t turn into a long series of guesswork, Memoria could be, with little doubt, one of the greatest point ‘n’ click adventure games: it will be difficult to find a story that is even on par with this one.Long version:Memoria is a direct sequel ofChains of Satinav, and as such it is also set in the world of Dark Eye, Germany’s most popular high fantasy table-top RPG setting.I cannot express how good the story of Memoria is. It is divided into two timelines: in one Geron (the protagonist from the previous game) is trying to change back his love to the way she used to be; and in the other we follow Sadja, a young woman who lived 450 years ago and tried to make her name immortal. They share a common mystery that is built with excellent pace, making you involved in the story more and more. And the solution/resolution is just perfect. It is not a happy ending, nor a sad one. It is bittersweet… it is surprising; it is everything a story needs.It also helps that the voice acting is significantly better than previously. All actors (but one) had great investment in their characters and gave a new emotional layer to the story.Sadly, the gameplay doesn’t reflect the greatness of the writing. The puzzles start mild, just the usual nonsensical adventure game logic. Then they threw in a forest maze (Broken Sword 2 style). After that, a long series of multi-guess combination puzzles, where figuring out the exact order of the right answers can take forever.Therefore, Memoria can be either a short 4-5 hour adventure or a 30+ hour one if you are unlucky with your guesses. And this can kill the mood really fast… even though this game could have been Daedelic Entertainment’s greatest masterpiece otherwise."
