76561197996684655,Recommended,243200,17826243,"Posted: 1 September, 2015",all,namtab,"Ok so hopefully if you're considering playing this it's because you've played through and enjoyed the wonderful Chains of Satinav and want more of Geron and Nuri. Well personally I felt that the Chains of Satinav was a better game because of it's story and characters, and although we are reintroduced to some old characters, a lot of the story takes place in the past with new characters. I say this not to put you off but just to let you know.The game itself is still great, and I would recomend it certainly. However the puzzles are a little less intuitive and often less rewarding than it's predecessor, the multiple screens and short animations make trial and error methods a little tedious, and more often than I'd like I found myself reaching out for an online guide.The animation has been greatly improved, those fantastic backdrops in CoS are even more beautiful in this game. Also the characters have been given a breath of fresh air in the form of a breathing animation that brings them to life and takes away that wooden feeling they gave you before. But the music in Memoria seems to have slipped in quality and doesn't quite have that melancholy atmosphere CoS had.In short although I do recommend this title and enjoyed playing it I felt it wasn't quite up to the standard of its predecessor. But don't let that put you off, they really caught lightning in a bottle with CoS in my opinion so it was pretty high standard to meet."
