76561198038625342,Recommended,243200,15009350,"Posted: 22 March, 2015",all,Dash,"Welcome back to Andergast!  The most racist and xenophobic city in the world.  A place where the people would sooner kill you then talk to you.  Taking place only 6 months after the ""The Chains of Satinav""  I kind of figured the main char would have fled the city to literally anywhere else.  Nope, he still lives there and gets treated like garbage, despite single handedly saving the city in the first game.  My guess is this was done to save some art assets from the first game, as I find it ludicrous that the main char would stick around this god forsaken town.Pretty much everything about Memoria is better than the first game.  The dialogue is better, the story is better, the voice acting is better, its longer, the puzzels are better.  It's by far the better game, sadly you definitely can not skip the first game in the series.  While this story definitely is completely different, the motivations of the main char are all tied to the first game, and they are constantly referencing events and characters from the first game.Perhaps the best part about Memoria is that the main char from the first game has the shortest sequences in this game.  You mainly play as a female wizard 500 years prior to the events of the first game.  This character has a far superior voice actor and better dialogue and is an all around more likeable protagonist.  Even better she is teamed up with a demonic magical staff which has fantastic dialogue and also a great voice actor.  I really hated the main char of Geron from the first game, I just didn't find him likeable at all, he's slightly better in this game, but still annoying.The game does still suffer from many of the issues in the first game though.  The lip sync with the dialogue is still atrocious.  They didn't even try to match it up, their mouths most of the time aren't even moving and when they do move they don't follow the words at all.  The music is bad in the sense that there is not enough music.  They should have background music for the whole game, in parts its just completely absent and in others it seems out of place with the actions happening on screen.Still, I think this is a good game.  I love the art direction again in this game and the puzzels are a lot more complex.  Nothing too drastically obtuse.  Except for a jungle maze puzzle, which they literally give you the option to skip, because it's pretty much impossible.  Get out your graph paper and start drawing if you want to figure this one out as it is absurd.  You definitely won't win it without mapping this thing out.  The very last puzzle is also a type of maze puzzle, but slightly easier.  I do wish they would continue making games in this series...but it kind of feels like this might be the last one.Anyone who likes adventure games should definitely get this game.  The story is fantastic, and genuinely had me interested the whole way through.  It's a lot more serious then the King's Quest games, but I enjoy that about it.  I still say it's not nearly as good as ""Gray Matter"" which I think is the best modern adventure game, but this is a must play for adventure game fans.  #Worth $5 (it is still an adventure game!)"
